arachni_report.title: Web Application Security Report - Arachni Framework

issue.name: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
issue.description: Client-side code (like JavaScript) can be injected into the web application which is then returned to the user's browser. This can lead to a compromise of the client's system or serve as a pivoting point for other attacks.
issue.remedy_guidance: User inputs must be validated and filtered before being returned as part of the HTML code of a page.

issue.name: SQL Injection
issue.description: SQL code can be injected into the web application.
issue.remedy_guidance: User inputs must be validated and filtered before being included in database queries.

remark.text: This issue was identified by a pattern but the pattern matched the page's response body even before auditing the logged element.

issue.name: Disclosed US Social Security Number (SSN)
issue.description: A US Social Security Number is being disclosed.
issue.remedy_guidance: Remove all SSN occurrences from the page.

issue.name: Unencrypted password form
issue.description: Transmission of password does not use an encrypted channel.
issue.remedy_guidance: Forms with sensitive content, like passwords, must be sent over HTTPS.

issue.name: Credit card number disclosure
issue.description: A credit card number is disclosed in the body of the page.
issue.remedy_guidance: Remove credit card numbers from the body of the HTML pages.

issue.name: Password field with auto-complete
issue.description: Some browsers automatically fill-in forms with sensitive user information for fields that don't have the auto-complete feature explicitly disabled.

issue.name: Directory listing
issue.description: In most circumstances enabling directory listings is a bad practice as it allows an attacker to better grasp the web application's structure.
issue.remedy_guidance: Restrict access to important directories or files by adopting a need to know requirement for both the document and server root, and turn off features such as Automatic Directory Listings.

issue.name: Allowed HTTP methods
issue.description: The webserver claims that it supports the logged methods.
issue.remedy_guidance: Configure your web server to disallow unnecessary HTTP method.

issue.name: Insecure cookie
issue.description: The logged cookie is allowed to be served over an unencrypted channel which makes it susceptible to sniffing.
issue.remedy_guidance: Set the 'Secure' flag in the cookie.

issue.name: Insecure cookie

issue.name: HttpOnly cookie
issue.description: The logged cookie does not have the HttpOnly flag set which makes it succeptible to maniplation via client-side code.
issue.remedy_guidance: Set the 'HttpOnly' flag in the cookie.
